</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="609" type="distribution">
<caption inLine="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="609" startId="12.[693,865,1159,1193]" targetBox="[78,670,852,1266]" targetPageId="12">
<paragraph blockId="12.[692,1285,848,1271]" pageId="12" pageNumber="609">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[693,869,1159,1193]" pageId="12" pageNumber="609">Distribution.</emphasis>
N DR Congo, N of the Congo River.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="609" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="12.[692,1285,848,1271]" lastBlockId="12.[80,1286,1286,1865]" pageId="12" pageNumber="609">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[693,936,1237,1271]" pageId="12" pageNumber="609">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head—body 89-124 mm, tail 51-72 mm, ear 11-16 mm, hindfoot 17-21 mm. No specific data are available for body weight. Dudu’s Brush-furred Ratis externally very similar to the Buff-spotted Brushfurred Rat (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1888" box="[245,474,1356,1390]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Lophuromys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="12" pageNumber="609" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="flavopunctatus">L. flavopunctatus</taxonomicName>
), but they have subtle differences in skull proportions.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
